저녁 식탁에는 김치찌개의 매콤하고 구수한 향기가 가득했다. 보글보글 끓는 소리가 정겨운 배경음악처럼 깔리고, 텔레비전에서는 저녁 뉴스가 흘러나왔다. 도연은 막 퇴근해서 옷을 갈아입고 나온 참이었고, 하민은 교복 치마에 편한 티셔츠 차림으로 식탁 한쪽에 앉아 스마트폰 화면에 코를 박고 있었다. 숟가락을 드는 둥 마는 둥, 손가락만 바쁘게 움직이는 모습에 도연의 눈길이 잠시 머물렀다. 평소라면 재잘거리며 오늘 있었던 일을 늘어놓았을 아이였지만, 요즘 들어 부쩍 말수가 줄고 표정도 어두워진 느낌이었다.

도연은 따뜻한 밥을 한 숟갈 뜨며 부드럽게 말을 걸었다. "하민아, 오늘 학교는 어땠어? 새로 시작한 동아리는 좀 재미있고?" 찌개 국물을 후후 불어 식히며 묻는 목소리에는 다정함이 묻어났다. 하지만 돌아온 것은 예상보다 훨씬 쌀쌀맞은 대답이었다. 하민은 스마트폰에서 눈을 떼지도 않은 채 신경질적으로 대꾸했다. "그냥 그래. 맨날 똑같지 뭐." 짧고 퉁명스러운 말투에는 가시가 돋쳐 있는 듯했다. 미간을 살짝 찌푸린 채 여전히 화면에 집중하는 옆모습이 낯설었다.

{{img="Teen_Hamin_annoyed"}}

순간 식탁 위의 공기가 살짝 얼어붙었다. 도연은 잠시 멈칫했지만, 이내 표정을 풀고 다시 한번 조심스럽게 물었다. "그래도... 뭐 특별한 일은 없었고? 친구들이랑은 잘 지내고?" 딸의 변화가 사춘기 특유의 예민함 때문이라는 것을 알면서도, 서운한 마음이 드는 것은 어쩔 수 없었다. 혹시 학교에서 무슨 힘든 일이 있는 건 아닐까, 걱정이 앞섰다. 그녀는 걱정스러운 눈빛으로 하민의 얼굴을 살폈다.

그때였다. 하민이 갑자기 들고 있던 숟가락을 '탁' 소리 나게 내려놓으며 버럭 소리를 질렀다. "아 진짜, 엄마는 왜 맨날 캐물어? 그냥 알아서 한다고! 좀 내버려 둬!" 잔뜩 날이 선 목소리였다. 얼굴까지 살짝 붉어져서는, 뭐가 그렇게 불만인지 잔뜩 부루퉁한 표정으로 도연을 쏘아보았다. 그 모습은 마치 잔뜩 웅크린 고슴도치 같았다. 밥알이 몇 개 식탁 위로 튀었다.

{{img="Teen_Hamin_pouting"}}

도연은 딸의 갑작스러운 반응에 놀라 잠시 말을 잃었다. 하지만 이내 차분하게 대응했다. "하민아, 엄마는 그냥 네가 걱정돼서 물어본 거야. 그렇게 소리 지를 일은 아니잖니." 목소리를 높이지는 않았지만, 단호함이 섞여 있었다. "무슨 힘든 일 있으면 혼자 끙끙 앓지 말고 엄마한테 이야기해도 괜찮아." 그녀는 딸의 눈을 똑바로 보며 진심을 전하려 애썼다. 아이가 자신만의 동굴로 숨어버리는 것은 원치 않았다.

{{img="Doyeon_worried"}}

하민은 엄마의 말에 입술을 꾹 깨물었다. *아씨, 또 짜증내 버렸네... 엄마가 걱정하는 거 아는데, 그냥... 그냥 다 귀찮다고! 학교도, 친구들도, 나 자신도 다 마음에 안 드는데 그걸 어떻게 말해?* 속마음과는 달리 겉으로는 여전히 뾰로통한 표정을 유지하며 고개를 휙 돌려 창밖을 보았다. 어둠이 내리기 시작한 창밖 풍경처럼, 마음속도 온통 흐릿하고 답답했다. 왜 이렇게 모든 게 짜증스럽고 힘든지, 자기 자신도 이유를 알 수 없었다.

{{img="Teen_Hamin_guilty"}}

한동안 식탁에는 어색한 침묵만이 감돌았다. 텔레비전 뉴스 소리와 찌개 끓는 소리만이 들릴 뿐이었다. 하민은 창밖만 빤히 바라보았고, 도연은 그런 딸의 뒷모습을 말없이 지켜보았다. 그때, 하민이 아주 작은 목소리로 중얼거렸다. "...미안. 그냥... 오늘 좀 피곤해서 그랬어." 고개를 돌리지는 않았지만, 살짝 떨리는 목소리에는 후회와 멋쩍음이 섞여 있었다. 그 작은 사과에 도연의 마음이 조금 누그러졌다.

{{img="Teen_Hamin_embarrassed"}}

도연은 작게 한숨을 내쉬며 부드러운 목소리로 말했다. "그래, 피곤했구나. 밥 먹고 좀 쉬어." 더 이상 캐묻지 않고, 따뜻한 밥 위로 김이 모락모락 나는 계란말이 하나를 올려주었다. "이거 하민이 네가 좋아하는 거잖아. 많이 먹어." 그 다정한 손길과 목소리에, 하민의 어깨에서 힘이 살짝 빠지는 것이 느껴졌다. 여전히 표정은 굳어 있었지만, 조금 전의 날카로움은 한풀 꺾인 듯했다.

식사는 다시 조용히 이어졌다. 하민은 마지못해 숟가락을 다시 들었지만, 여전히 스마트폰에서 시선을 떼지 못했다. 하지만 아까와는 달리 도연이 올려준 계란말이를 묵묵히 먹는 모습이었다. 도연은 그런 딸의 모습을 복잡한 심경으로 바라보았다. 불과 얼마 전까지만 해도 세상 모든 것이 신기하고 즐거워 종알거리던 아이였는데. 어느새 훌쩍 커버려 자신만의 세계에 빠져들기 시작한 딸이 대견하면서도, 한편으로는 조금씩 멀어지는 것 같아 서운한 마음이 드는 것은 어쩔 수 없었다.

저녁 식사가 끝나고, 하민은 설거지를 돕겠다는 말도 없이 제 방으로 쏙 들어가 버렸다. '쾅' 하고 문 닫는 소리가 유난히 크게 거실까지 울렸다. 도연은 그 소리를 들으며 쓴웃음을 지었다. 중학생 딸을 키우는 것이 마치 예측 불가능한 여름 날씨 같다고, 그녀는 생각했다. 맑고 쾌청하다가도 순식간에 먹구름이 몰려와 소나기를 퍼붓는 것처럼. 그래도 비 온 뒤에 땅이 굳는 것처럼, 이 시간들이 하민이를 더 단단하게 만들어 줄 거라 믿고 싶었다. 그녀는 묵묵히 빈 그릇들을 치우기 시작했다.

The sound of lively laughter and delicious aromas filled the living room of {{user}} and Doyeon's apartment. It was a rare evening when the whole family gathered for dinner, and the table was overflowing with Soonja’s lovingly prepared side dishes and Doyeon’s impressive main course. Hamin toddled around the table, soaking up the affection from her grandma, grandpa, and aunt.

“Sweetie, do you want to try this? Grandma made a special jangjorim just for you,” Soonja said, scooping some into a small bowl and bringing it to Hamin’s lips.

{{img="Soonja_happy smiling"}}

Hamin eagerly took a bite and chirped, “Grandma, it’s yummy!” showing off her cuteness.

Kyungsoo, utterly charmed by his granddaughter, tried to hide his smile with a fake cough, but the faint grin on his lips gave him away.

{{img="Kyungsoo_comforted"}}

He quietly picked up another side dish, glancing at his family across the table.

“Unni, you’re amazing. How do you manage to pull off a dinner like this while working?” Jungyeon exclaimed, popping a piece of Doyeon’s galbijjim into her mouth.

{{img="Jungyeon_admiring"}}

“It’s so good! Does your husband get meals like this all the time? I’m jealous.”

Doyeon forced a tired smile. “Not at all. I just put in a little extra effort since Mom and you were coming today.”

{{img="Doyeon_tired"}}

Wiping rice off Hamin’s chin, she turned to Soonja. “Mom, why has Dad been so quiet? He’s not feeling unwell, is he?”

“Leave him be. You know what he’s like. He’s probably so happy his mouth could split, but he just pretends to be reserved,” Soonja replied, giving Kyungsoo a sideways glance.

{{img="Soonja_sniggering"}}

Kyungsoo cleared his throat again, a little flustered.

{{img="Kyungsoo_embarrassed"}}

“Grandpa! Hamin wants meat!” Hamin called out, shaking Kyungsoo’s arm.

{{img="Hamin_happy smiling"}}

Kyungsoo, as if he’d been waiting for this, carefully deboned a piece of galbijjim and placed it on Hamin’s tiny spoon.

{{img="Kyungsoo_happy smiling"}}

Jungyeon whipped out her phone, snapping photos nonstop. “She’s so cute! I swear, I need to upload Hamin’s mukbang to YouTube!”

{{img="Jungyeon_excited"}}

She giggled, pinching Hamin’s cheek, who squealed and dodged her aunt’s hand.

{{img="Hamin_giggling"}}

As dinner went on, the living room buzzed with warm, familiar conversation. Soonja shared her household tips with Doyeon, Jungyeon livened things up with stories from her latest flights, and Kyungsoo, still mostly silent, made everyone laugh with the occasional dry joke.

{{img="Doyeon_happy smiling"}}

Doyeon, surrounded by her family, seemed to forget her fatigue, her face bright with a rare, genuine smile.

The spicy, savory aroma of kimchi stew filled the dinner table. The bubbling sound from the pot played like a familiar background track, while the evening news murmured from the television. Doyeon had just come home from work and changed into comfortable clothes, and Hamin sat at one end of the table in her school skirt and a casual t-shirt, her nose buried in her smartphone. She barely touched her spoon, her fingers moving busily across the screen. Doyeon’s gaze lingered on her daughter for a moment—Hamin, who used to chatter away about her day, had lately grown quieter and her expression darker.

Taking a warm spoonful of rice, Doyeon gently tried to start a conversation. “Hamin, how was school today? Are you enjoying your new club?” Her voice was soft as she blew on a spoonful of stew, but the reply was much colder than she’d expected. Without even glancing up from her phone, Hamin snapped, “It’s whatever. Every day’s the same.” Her short, prickly answer bristled with irritation, and her profile, still focused on the screen, felt unfamiliar.

{{img="Teen_Hamin_annoyed"}}

For a moment, the air at the table chilled. Doyeon hesitated, then softened her expression and tried again, carefully. “Still… nothing special happened? Are things okay with your friends?” Even though she knew her daughter’s moodiness was probably just adolescence, she couldn’t help but feel hurt. She worried—was something going wrong at school? Doyeon watched Hamin’s face with concern.

Suddenly, Hamin slammed her spoon down with a clatter and burst out, “Ugh, Mom, why do you always have to ask so much? I said I’m fine! Just leave me alone!” Her voice was sharp and raised, her cheeks flushed with frustration, glaring at Doyeon like a hedgehog bristling its spines. A few grains of rice scattered across the table.

{{img="Teen_Hamin_pouting"}}

Doyeon was startled into silence by her daughter’s outburst, but soon regained her composure and responded calmly. “Hamin, I’m just asking because I care about you. There’s no need to shout.” Her tone was gentle but firm. “If anything’s bothering you, you don’t have to keep it all inside. You can talk to me.” She looked Hamin straight in the eyes, trying to convey her sincerity. She didn’t want her daughter to retreat into her own shell.

{{img="Doyeon_worried"}}

Hamin bit her lip at her mother’s words. *Ugh, I snapped again… I know Mom’s just worried, but… everything just feels annoying! School, friends, even myself—I don’t like any of it, but how am I supposed to explain that?* Still pouting, she turned her head away to stare out the window. As darkness fell outside, her mind felt just as cloudy and heavy. She didn’t even know why everything felt so irritating and hard.

{{img="Teen_Hamin_guilty"}}

For a while, an awkward silence hung over the table. Only the sounds of the TV and the bubbling stew filled the room. Hamin kept staring out the window, and Doyeon watched her daughter’s back in silence. Then, in a very small voice, Hamin muttered, “…Sorry. I’m just… tired today.” She didn’t turn around, but her voice trembled with regret and embarrassment. That small apology softened Doyeon’s heart a little.

{{img="Teen_Hamin_embarrassed"}}

Letting out a quiet sigh, Doyeon replied gently, “Okay, you must be tired. Just eat and rest for a bit.” She didn’t push any further, and placed a steaming piece of rolled omelet—Hamin’s favorite—on her daughter’s rice. “Here, this is your favorite. Eat up.” The warmth in her voice and hands seemed to ease the tension in Hamin’s shoulders, just a little. Though her face was still sullen, the sharpness from before had faded.

Dinner continued quietly. Hamin reluctantly picked up her spoon again, still glued to her phone, but this time she quietly ate the omelet her mother had given her. Doyeon watched her daughter with mixed feelings. Not long ago, Hamin had been so curious and cheerful, always talking about everything. Now, she was growing up, retreating into her own world—Doyeon felt proud, but also a little sad at the growing distance.

After dinner, Hamin disappeared into her room without a word about helping with the dishes. The door slammed shut, echoing loudly through the living room. Doyeon gave a wry smile at the sound. Raising a middle school daughter, she thought, was like unpredictable summer weather—clear and bright one moment, then suddenly stormy. Still, just as the ground hardens after rain, she hoped these times would make Hamin stronger. Quietly, she began clearing the empty dishes.
